Weather-Respiratory Diseases Correlation Explorer

Team MMI

2024-12-11

Project

This dashboard aims to investigate the relationship between climate and weather-related conditions and outbreaks of two respiratory viruses, influenza and respiratory syncytial virus (RSV).

Influenza is an RNA virus from the Orthomyxoviridae family that frequently mutates, causing seasonal epidemics, while RSV is an RNA virus from the Paramyxoviridae family that primarily affects young children and the elderly, often leading to severe lower respiratory infections. Both viruses pose significant public health challenges due to their widespread transmission and potential for severe disease.

Climate and weather conditions can influence the activity and spread of both viruses. Studies have suggested that factors like cold temperatures, low indoor humidity, limited sunlight, and rapid weather changes may increase the risk of disease outbreaks.

Features

Weekly Rates

This dashboard uses CDC RESP-NET data to give an overview of influenza and rsv hospitalization rates of each state from 2018 to 2024. The user can select year, state, and pathogen of interest using the interactive filters.

Weather Explorer

This dashboard integrated environmental parameter data from openmeteo API and respiratory virus-associated hospitalization rate data to perform regression analysis. The user can select year, state, weather variable and pathogen of interest using the interactive filters.

Data

Respiratory Virus Related Hospitalization Rate

Disease rate data were scrapped from CDC RESP-NET. Note that both viruses seasonalities have changed significantly during and after the COVID-19 pandemic.

Summary of Influenza Data

Summary of RSV Data

Environmental Parameters

Weather data were scrapped from Openmeteo API.

Correlation Heatmap

From the figure below, we can see that respiratory virus associated hospitalization rate (weekly_rate) has the highest correlation with maximum and minimum daily temperature, sunshine, daylight, shortwave radiation, and evaporation.

Data Dictionary

Here is an overview of the combined dataset of weekly environmental parameters and respiratory virus-related hospitalization rates used for data analysis and dashboard building.

Variable Description Unit
site U.S. state participated in RESP-Net /
weekly_rate weekly respiratory virus-related hospitalization rate per 100,000
cumulative_rate cumulative respiratory virus-related hospitalization rate per 100,000
date date at end of the corresponding epidemiological week /
year year /
week epidemiological week /
y_w year and epidemiological week combined /
pathogen respiratory virus type /
temp_max maximum daily temperature (weekly average) C
temp_min minimum daily temperature (weekly average) C
precip_sum sum of precipitation - rain and snow (weekly average) mm
precip_hr duration of precipitation - rain and snow (weekly average) hours
sunshine duration of sunshine (weekly average) seconds
daylight duration of daylight (weekly average) seconds
wind_speed_max maximum windspeed (weekly average) km/h
wind_gusts_max maximum gusts (weekly average) km/h
wind_direction dominant wind direction (weekly average)
shortwave sum of solar radiation (weekly average) MJ/m
evapo sum of ET0 Reference Evapotranspiration of a well watered grass field (weekly average) mm
